{
  "texts": [
    "IntroductionWith the European Union's Digital Services Act (referred to as the 'DSA') [57] entering into force in late 2022 and fully applicable from February 2024, a timely and urgent opportunity emerges to empirically evaluate if its mechanisms can meaningfully constrain opaque algorithms, advertisers and platforms implicated in online harms.In particular, the rise of highly capable and scarcely regulated Artificial Intelligence (AI) applications on online platform raise urgent questions around how algorithmic governance must adapt to grapple with emerging societal risks [26,81,126,127,129,150,164,179].",
    "Particularly, recent advances in generative AI, driven by massive internettrained language models, enable automated generation of text, images and other content that appears authentic [7,16,20,32,39,73,113,132,146,171,177,188].",
    "Nevertheless, these opaque systems also have the potential to generate manipulative content, disseminate harmful disinformation, and perpetuate systematic biases on a massive scale without meaningful human oversight or transparency [1,13,25,40,72,80,84,95,103,117,128,131,133,151,155,156].",
    "Precisely with this purpose of tackling issues such as disinformation and preventing harmful activities online, the DSA aims to ensure transparency across platforms, establish accountability mechanisms, and create specific provisions addressing emerging social risks posed by opaque algorithmic systems.",
    "For instance, it aims to address disinformation spread via algorithmic recommender systems, behavioral advertising, and electoral integrity.However, comprehensive empirical assessments of the DSA's effectiveness in mitigating emerging social harms from AI and other widely deployed opaque algorithmic applications, remain lacking to date."
  ]
}